One thing about the RNAME field that has always puzzled me is the
fact that the at-sign "@" that normally appears in RFC822 addresses
seems to be replaced by a dot when it appears in this field of an
SOA record. Is this really the case? Why?  Is this specified anywhere?
All I can find in RFC883 is an example using dots only:

    @   IN  SOA     F.ISI.ARPA       Action.E.ISI.ARPA (             

In appendix 2:

         RNAME   - A domain name which specifies the mailbox of the
                   person responsible for this zone.

But later it says:
	 The RDATA section of a SOA line in a master file is a standard
	 printed domain name for MNAME, a standard X@Y mailbox
	 specification for RNAME, and decimal numbers for the remaining
	 parameters.

So should the "@" appear or not?

	Thanks, Bill Nowicki
		Sun Microsystems

